---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Start Blue | Franco Lopez" description="Start Blue is a Kubernetes-based quote platform used by 350+ LS Tractor dealers across the US and Canada.">
  <header class="page-header">
    <span class="eyebrow">production platform · 350+ dealers</span>
    <h1>Start Blue</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      A Kubernetes-based quote platform used by LS Tractor dealers across the United States and Canada.
    </p>
    <div class="actions">
      <a class="button primary" href="https://startblue.lstractorusa.com">Visit platform</a>
      <a class="button" href="/projects/">Back to projects</a>
    </div>
  </header>

  <article class="content">
    <h2>Problem</h2>
    <p>
      Dealer quote workflows needed a centralized system that could support real business use across a
      large dealer network instead of relying on scattered manual processes.
    </p>

    <h2>What I built</h2>
    <p>
      I designed and operated Start Blue as a cloud-hosted, containerized quote platform with React
      workflows, PostgreSQL data storage, Kubernetes deployment, analytics, and business reporting.
    </p>

    <h2>Architecture</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>React frontend for dealer quote workflows</li>
      <li>PostgreSQL backend data layer</li>
      <li>Containerized application workloads</li>
      <li>Kubernetes deployment model</li>
      <li>Cloud-hosted infrastructure with operational ownership</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Operational concerns</h2>
    <p>
      The important part was not only writing the application. It had to be deployable, supportable,
      understandable by the business, and reliable enough for a distributed dealer audience.
    </p>

    <h2>Impact</h2>
    <p>
      Start Blue is used by 350+ dealers across the US and Canada. It is the clearest example on this
      site of the work I want to do more of: building practical platforms that combine software,
      infrastructure, deployment, and operations.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
